commentBody:
@David G 
Hmm you're more right than I first thought.  I had thought that perhaps some non-T-marked Ts remained in a couple of words, but no, all the Ts are superfluous to the real answers, and all disappear.  So what WAS the point of marking the squares with giant transparent T shapes?  Shading, at most, would have been fine.

Also, it still kind of bugs me that in EVERY case there are multiple Ts in a word/phrase, and yet the revealer says that Tea, singular, leaves.  Not the greatest cluing, unless I've missed something....

@Ilka 

I'll bet you have an error somewhere in the rest of the puzzle.

Others are saying they had no trouble.

@Ilka try on the website instead of the app. I still had to "rig" (fix? really?) it to get the fill, but it worked hella better than the app. 

really was a bad idea. 

Time for a rule: if it can't be done in the paper (disappearing "t", or other funky stuff), then don't do it on the app. if ever there comes a day when print is truly dead, then have at it with the little coding clues. until then, use the KISS method for constructing these.

@Jere Hallahan 

The newspaper version looks exactly the same.

I don't have a print edition in front of me, but on a browser, if you click the print icon, you'll get the option to get the newspaper version.  You can see it onscreen without having to print it.

@Eric 
I looked askance at that, too....but then I thought, "He's GONE PRO" might be a statement that fit the way it's clued, so I moved on.


And thought about recipes for emu meat...

@Blurry 

I did not even realize it was a cartoon!
I am a cartoon fan, but....I don't think there was a Martian in the ones we used to see (after the News of the Day and the previews and ads, before the feature film at the movie theater...)  .....Yep, I go way back.

@William Schrader 

Ha ha, regarding "two Luddites".

Now come on, don't exaggerate.  Counting @Times Rita, @retired, with cat, @Mean Old Lady and me, we're already up to 4.  There may be a few others as well.......

@G. L. Dryfoos - just ballparking from another angle:
all those squares already had a letter in them.

Why would anybody type in a square that already has a letter in it? 🧐

@Ken 

I solved on Android, didn't touch the "T" squares, and had no problem getting the gold star. And, had fun doing it. 

I think the note was a matter of "just in case, try these things".

@R.J. Smith 
There was one!  At the ACPT in 2023.  It was an April Fool's joke, and every clue could be answered with the word "blank."  
It was my first time there, so it was the first puzzle I was ever given in a live competition.  Oh boy, did I freak out for a minute before I saw more experienced solvers chuckling and raising their hands to indicate they were finished. One of many fond memories from that weekend.

@Voicers 

The puzzle elves will gladly restore you streak.  About all you have to do is ask them.  

It's not like a streak is worth anything to anyone other than the streak-holder.

@JMGIII 
This is one of of the differences between Android and iOS. The i blinks in the iOS app when there's a note.  Why it doesn't in Android is above my pay grade. 

Because I am interested in seeing  who the constructor is before solving (and the Sunday title), I'm in the habit of checking the info everyday. It hardly takes a minute, so I recommend that everyone take a look, and that way you'll never miss a note.

@Shimmer 

Good thing you said IMHO, since it’s just your opinion. AONE has been an answer 650 times, with today’s exact clue used 20 times since Shortz  started. This is not going to change. 

Spelling out numbers that are not spelled out in real life is very normal in crosswords, like it or not.

@SJS 

Give it a day or so. If your gold star tuns blue, email the games team and ask them to restore your streak. 

I’ve done that a few times.
